Or he has really big hands, much bigger than his head. Or the ape shown at 2:04 is not really Kong, but a "smaller" ape? Which means that the handprint at 1:03 belongs to the real Kong.  Because if the ape at 2:04 is really Kong....then that's waaay too small. Probably only 100-150feet tall maximum. Which would be too small to fight against Godzilla.  Unless if by the time Kong fights Godzilla in the 21st century, he magically doubles or triples his size. To double his size in 40-50 years? Seems very unlikely (but then again, we don't how old Kong is in the new movie. If he grew to his current size in 40-50 years, then it may be possible, but that would mean he's just a little kid ape in the new reboot movie. Lol. But if he's already an "adult" in the reboot, it doesn't seem very likely for him to double/triple his size by the time he fights Godzilla.)  Unless if the Kong vs. Godzilla movie is to be set before the 21st century, and Godzilla is smaller....waaay smaller.  In any case, this movie seems promising. Looking forward to it. text: I'm one of the biggest King Kong fans in the world, and I do not like what I'm seeing here. In fact, I haven't been onboard with this new direction they're taking one of my most beloved characters ever since I heard about this project. This isn't King Kong at all. This is an oversized, inaccurate portrayal of Kong in order to make him into another Kaiju monster able to fight Godzilla on-screen in a few more years. These two characters come from two entirely different types of fiction to begin with. Godzilla is a 1950s era, atomic age/space age science fiction character with the ability to destroy the entire human race. King Kong is from the early 20th century era of "lost world" fiction— a genre more about adventure, exploration, and using new technologies to discover lands that time forgot. There's nothing these two stalwarts have in common other than being very big and primal. But Godzilla isn't just "big" like Kong; Godzilla is enormous! Kong is really only about 28 ft tall, whereas Godzilla is 400+ ft tall and has atomic breath. The more fitting idea for a crossover blockbuster fight movie would be Jurassic Park vs. King Kong, not Kong and Godzilla.

The original was a reflection on humanities destructive nature. This one looks more like an action brawl. - I loved the trailers of Godzilla as well but the final movie, while not a failure, was still very disappointing (Bad pacing, non-sense story, The only memorable character is killed off within the first act, boring protagonist). text: So, Kong is big. Really big. With a really big head, and, almost certainly, a really big brain. A creature with a brain that size is almost certainly sentient, the chances of anything other than that being infinitesimal. Creatures have big brains in order to be intelligent, so without questioning how something with the bone structure of a great ape can even walk at that size, Kong _must_ be a genius. They have to be. It's an evolutionary fact, because even if they're uneducated in any formal fashion, their lifespan must dwarf ours, and in all that time I think it's safe to say that they've probably learned a few things. So, it follows that a creature of that intelligence and power could easily wipe out the human race. Not through brute strength, but through knowledge, knowledge used to create technological marvels that make our supercomputers look like stone wheels. So, again, it follows that they chose otherwise. Whether they don't care about humans or whether they pity us, I don't know, but I'm calling that as the "big twist" of the film.

text: For those of you that didn't take time to research the plot. Kong: Skull Island is confirmed to be taking place in the same universe as Legendary Pictures' Godzilla, but it is set in the year 1971, placing it after the U.S. military used an atomic bomb in an attempt to kill Godzilla in 1954 but before the main events of the film in 1999 and 2014. The scientific organization Monarch from Godzilla will be featured in this film to further tie it into Godzilla. The film will likely include references to Godzilla and feature allusions to the upcoming film Godzilla 2 in order to build up to Godzilla vs. Kong in 2020.

text: Love how the trailer is fundamentally different to Godzilla's.   The Big G's had a lot of red and black, epic music and choir and a very clear message: Natures has a food chain, and humanity is way, waaaaay at the bottom, to point where its virtually pointless to try and challenge the big guys.  Meanwhile, this one is a lot more primal. Lots of color, lots of jolts, very tribal music and basically the opposite of Godzilla: Man has entered another world. An older world. It either fights it or die.      Of course, this is the setup for Godzilla vs King Kong, so we know who's gonna win this round of Man vs Monster.

text: An excellent retake or reboot of the Kong Mythology with a killer soundtrack that fits perfectly with what was being played during the Vietnam War & also fits perfectly within this new hostile & even more dangerous environment that these troops & scientists have been dropped into...  My only concern when I heard Godzilla vs Kong was green lit/before Godzilla King Of The Monsters came out/was how they put these 2 protagonists on a collision course!...  As they are both not the antagonists but the keepers of the balance of life on the perspective of these movies, but now after seeing Godzilla vs Kong I think that someone will use the " Orca " (not giving anything away if you haven't seen this film) to pit both against each other... As I just don't see why these 2 Titans would square off in this particular take on these character's...  If it was the older movies I could understand it as it was just kaiju action non stop with Godzilla being pitted against these other Titans & Godzilla always came out on top...  It'll be interesting to see how they pit these 2 Titans against each other & I'm guessing it'll be a draw at the end as both are not the antagonists in these particular movie reboots...   .....
